Use lm to fit the following linear models:

Categorical variables only - linear additive

mod1 <- lm(y ~ region + customer, data = dfii)

Continuous variables only - linear additive

mod2 <- lm(y ~ ., data = dfii %>% select(starts_with("x"), y))

All categorical and continuous variables - linear additive

mod3 <- lm(y ~ ., data = dfii %>% select(!c( "response", "outcome")))

Interact region with continuous inputs, do not include customer

mod4 <- lm(y ~ region * (.-region), data = dfii %>% select(!c("customer", "response", "outcome")))

Interact customer with continuous inputs, do not include region

mod5 <- lm(y ~ customer * (.-customer), data = dfii %>% select(!c("region", "response", "outcome")))

All pairwise interactions of continuous inputs, do not include categorical inputs

mod6 <- lm(y ~ (.)^2, data = dfii %>% select(starts_with("x"), y))

3 models with basis functions of your choice

dfii <- df_all %>% 
  mutate(y = log(response)) %>% 
  select(region,customer,y)
mod7 <- lm(y~.^2, data = dfii)
dfii <- df_all %>% 
  mutate(y = log(response)) %>% 
  select(starts_with('xs'),y)
mod8 <- lm(y~.^2, data = dfii)
dfii <- df_all %>% 
  mutate(y = log(response)) %>% 
  select(region,customer,y)
mod9 <- lm(y ~ customer*region, data = dfii)

Which of the 9 models is the best? What performance metric did you use to make your selection?

extract_metrics <- function(my_mod, mod_name)
{
  broom::glance(my_mod) %>% 
    mutate(model_name = mod_name)
}

all_model_metrics <- purrr::map2_dfr(list(mod1, 
                                          mod2, 
                                          mod3, 
                                          mod4, 
                                          mod5, 
                                          mod6,  
                                          mod7,

                                       "mod2",

                                       "mod8", 
                                       "mod9"), 
                                     extract_metrics)
all_model_metrics %>%

Which inputs seem important?

How does the lm() maximum likelihood estimate

(MLE) on 𝜎 relate to the posterior uncertainty on 𝜎?

as.data.frame(bayes_mod3) %>% tibble::as_tibble() %>% 
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = sigma)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 150) +

             color = "red", linetype = "dashed", size = 3)
